<!--Comment Syntax.-->
<!-- This file contains basic HTML tags learned through Codecademy -->

<!-- Basic html layout looks like this. Any opening tag with <> must end with </> --> 
<!DOCTYPE html> 
  <!-- tells the web browser to expect an HTML document-->
<html> 
  <!-- root of the html document and a parent of all other elements on webpage-->
  
<head> 
  <!-- includes all metadata about the site including title-->
  <title> the site's title, users find this title through search engine </title>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <!-- tells the web browser which character set to use. UTF-8 is defaul character set for HTML 5 -->
</head>
<body>
  the content of the website
</body>
</html>

<!-- Basics Tags-->
<h1> through <h6> This dictates the size of your headings
<p> Paragragh tag
<img src="http://www.imagename.com"/> image tag, they are self closing
<a href="http://www.sitename.com"> Links to site </a>

<ol>
  <li>ordered lists contain numbers</li> <!--you can also bed lists within lists -->
</ol>

<ul>
  <li> unorderlists contain bullets </li>
</ul>

<font-family: Font name>
<font-size: 10px or 1rem or 2em> rem represents default size of web browser, so 1rem=16px, 2rem=32px, 3rem=48px etc. 
<font-weight: bold or italic>
<color: red or HEX# >
<background-color: red>
<background-image: url(http://www....")>
<strong> This creates bold words </strong>
<em> This create italic words </em>
<border: 2px solid red;> This property supports a few values
<border-radius> This property modifies the corners of your HTML objects
<margin: auto> This sets the margin with equal sides on the HTML element
<text-align: center> Aligns text to center
<line-height: 20px> This give a height to an line of text
<text-transform: uppercase> This makes text uppercase
<letter-spacing: 2px;> Puts space inbetween each letter


<!-- you can also add styling right into tags, see below -->
<p style="font-size: 12px"></p>
<h1 style="color: red"></h1>

<!--TABLE TAGS-->
<table  table border="1px"> creates a border around the table
    <thead> Is the table head tag which can be thought of as containing information about a table 
      <tr>
        <th colspan="3"> Is used to name a table column header </th>
        <!--the colspan tag is used to make the table header span across the rows by setting the artribute to the
        number of columns-->
      </tr>
    </thead>
      <tbody> Is the table body tag which contains the actual tabular data.
        <tr> This creates a table row but no data goes here 
            <td> This is where you put the table data </td>
            <td> By adding a second td tag it creates a second column in the same row </td>
        </tr>  
      </tbody>
</table>

<!--DIV TAG-->
<div> This tag allows you to divide your page into containers 
</div>

<!-- Three properties of the <div> tag are background-color, width and height -->



<!-- SPAN TAG-->
<span> allows you to control styling for smaller parts of your page, such as text. 
For example <span style="color:red">red!</span> This makes only the word 'red!' red.

The relationship of html, head and body: 
<html> <!--The trunk of the tree!-->
	<head> <!--Child of html, parent of title,
		   sibling of body-->
		<title></title> <!--Immediate child of head,
						child of head AND html-->
	</head>
	<body> <!--Child of html, parent of p,
		   sibling of head-->
		<p></p> <!--Immediate child of body,
				child of body AND html-->
	</body>
</html>

<!-- Common Page Structure -->
<head> ... </head>
	<section> Used to identify a thematic group, which generally in cludes a heading. 
	Commonly used to break up and provide heirarch to a page </section>
	<article> Used to identify a large piece of content like blog posts, article or user generated content </article>
	<aside> holds content such as sidebars, links, inserts or brief explanations </aside>
	<footer> ...</footer>
